Note:
TOML Parser - Builds a nested AST from TOML tokens

This file implements parsing for TOML v1.0.0, building a proper hierarchical
tree rather than a flat dotted-key list:

- Key-value pairs            (key = value)
- Dotted keys                (a.b.c = value -> nested tables)
- Tables                     ([table.name] -> nested table dictionaries)
- Array of tables            ([[array.table]] -> arrays of table dictionaries)
- Arrays                     ([v1, v2, ...])
- Inline tables              ({k = v, ...})
- All TOML scalar data types (string, integer, float, boolean, datetime)

The document is modeled as a root TOML_TABLE whose keys/children Lists run in
parallel. A [table] header navigates (creating intermediate tables as needed)
to the table the subsequent key/value pairs attach to. A [[array.table]]
header gets-or-creates a TOML_ARRAY at the named slot and appends a fresh
TOML_TABLE element, which becomes the active table. Dotted keys (a.b = v)
create the same nested-table structure as [a] then b = v.

This nested model is what lets toml_to_hir lower tables to nested HIR
dictionary literals and arrays-of-tables to HIR array literals of dictionaries,
which in turn lets the round-trip back to TOML reproduce the structure.

Dependencies:
- toml_lexer.runa (for tokenization)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/toml/toml_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOML AST Node Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TOML_DOCUMENT as Integer is 200
Constant TOML_TABLE as Integer is 201
Constant TOML_ARRAY as Integer is 202
Constant TOML_INLINE_TABLE as Integer is 203
Constant TOML_STRING as Integer is 204
Constant TOML_INTEGER as Integer is 205
Constant TOML_FLOAT as Integer is 206
Constant TOML_BOOLEAN as Integer is 207
Constant TOML_DATETIME as Integer is 208

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOML AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A single node shape covers every TOML construct (document, table, array, inline
table, all scalars). Tables and inline tables use the parallel keys/children
lists; arrays and arrays-of-tables use children only; scalars use value_string
(strings/floats/datetimes) or value_int (integers/booleans). Keeping one layout
lets the translator dispatch on node_type and the parser reuse one allocator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Ten 8-byte fields: type discriminator, value_string pointer, value_int,
is_integer flag, is_float flag, children list, keys list (parallel to children
for tables/inline-tables), table_name pointer, source line and column.
@End Implementation

Type called "TOMLNode":
    node_type as Integer        Note: TOML_* constant
    value_string as Integer     Note: String value (for strings/floats/datetimes)
    value_int as Integer        Note: Integer value (for integers/booleans)
    is_integer as Integer       Note: Boolean: 1 if value is integer
    is_float as Integer         Note: Boolean: 1 if value is float
    children as Integer         Note: List of child nodes (for arrays/tables)
    keys as Integer             Note: List of keys (for tables/inline tables)
    table_name as Integer       Note: Full table name (unused in nested model; kept for ABI)
    line as Integer             Note: Line number in source
    column as Integer           Note: Column number in source
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOML Parser Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The TOML parser is a streaming cursor pulling one token at a time from the
lexer. It tracks the document root and the currently-active table so that
key/value pairs and [table] headers can navigate the nested structure without
re-scanning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five 8-byte slots: lexer pointer, current_token pointer, owned error_message
string (or 0), has_error flag, and the active table node (the TOML_TABLE that
subsequent key/value pairs attach to).
@End Implementation

Type called "TOMLParser":
    lexer as Integer            Note: TOML lexer
    current_token as Integer    Note: Current token
    error_message as Integer    Note: Error message (if any)
    has_error as Integer        Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
    current_table as Integer    Note: Active TOML_TABLE node for key/value attachment
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Priming the parser with the lexer's first token at construction lets every
parse_* routine assume current_token is always valid (or EOF), avoiding a
per-call "have we started yet?" check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 40 bytes; null-check. Store the lexer pointer; null out current_token /
error_message / has_error / current_table. Pull the first token from the lexer
and write it to the current_token slot.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_toml_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create TOML parser with lexer

    Let parser_size be 40  Note: TOMLParser: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0   Note: current_token = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0  Note: has_error = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, 0  Note: current_table = null

    Note: Advance to first token
    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser owns any heap-allocated error message; destruction must release it
to prevent leaks when the parse fails and the caller discards the parser.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-check the parser. Read the error_message pointer at offset 16; if non-null
deallocate. Deallocate the parser block.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_toml_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy TOML parser

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Token advancement is the most-called helper and must be cheap; isolating it in
one routine guarantees the cached current_token slot stays in sync with the
lexer cursor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Pull the lexer pointer from offset 0, request the next token from the lexer,
and store it at offset 8. Return the new token pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, token

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Every parse decision begins with a token-type inspection; returning TOKEN_EOF
for null tokens lets callers compare safely without an explicit null guard.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the current_token at offset 8; if null return TOKEN_EOF. Otherwise read
the type tag at the token's offset 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current token type

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate-style lookahead is needed in many parse decisions; wrapping
peek_token_type plus an equality check keeps caller code linear.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Call peek_token_type and return 1 if equal to expected_type, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches expected type

    Let actual_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If actual_type is equal to expected_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A mandatory-token helper turns "required syntax" checks into single-line calls
and ensures every miss writes a uniform error message before short-circuiting.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compare peek_token_type to expected_type; on mismatch call set_parse_error with
the provided message and return 0. On match, advance the cursor and return 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect token of specific type, set error if mismatch

    Let actual_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If actual_type is not equal to expected_type:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multiple consecutive blank lines are legal between TOML statements; consuming
all of them in one helper keeps the parse_document loop linear.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop: if current token is TOKEN_NEWLINE advance and continue; otherwise break.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_newlines" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip any newline tokens

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_newline be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NEWLINE from Lexer

        If is_newline is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Recording the first parse error requires copying the message into parser-owned
storage so the original message buffer's lifetime is independent of the parser.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the current error_message; if non-null free it. Measure the new message,
allocate length+1 bytes, copy, null-terminate. Store the pointer at offset 16
and set has_error=1 at offset 24.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Error messages typically come from internal callers; the length-driven copy
bounds memory usage regardless of message origin.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "set_parse_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set parser error message

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    Let msg_length be proc string_length from StringCore with message
    Let new_error be proc allocate from Layout with msg_length plus 1

    If new_error is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_copy from Layout with new_error, message, msg_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with new_error, msg_length, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, new_error
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 1  Note: has_error = true

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Centralised node allocation initialises every TOMLNode slot to zero so
downstream readers cannot observe uninitialised memory if a field never gets
populated by the specific parse_* helper.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 80 bytes; null-check. Store the type at offset 0 and zero every other
slot (value_string, value_int, is_integer, is_float, children, keys,
table_name, line, column).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_toml_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create TOML AST node

    Let node_size be 80  Note: TOMLNode: 10 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0   Note: value_string = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0  Note: value_int = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0  Note: is_integer = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0  Note: is_float = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0  Note: children = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0  Note: keys = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, 0  Note: table_name = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, 0  Note: line = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, 0  Note: column = 0

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tables and inline tables share the parallel keys/children layout; a dedicated
constructor that pre-creates both backing lists keeps every table-producing
path from re-implementing the two-list initialisation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Create a node of the given type. Create two empty Lists and store them at the
children (offset 40) and keys (offset 48) slots. Return the node (0 on any
allocation failure).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_table_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a table-shaped node with parallel keys/children lists

    Let node be proc create_toml_node with node_type

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc create from List
    Let keys be proc create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, children
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, keys

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Table Navigation Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Within a table's parallel keys/children lists, locating an existing entry by
name is needed both to merge dotted keys / repeated [table] prefixes and to
detect redefinitions. Content comparison (string_equals) is correct because
each key is a distinct heap copy; pointer identity would never match.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the keys and children lists. Linear-scan the keys with string_equals; on
a content match return the parallel child at the same index. Return 0 if the
name is absent or the table has no lists.
@End Implementation

Process called "table_find_child" takes table_node as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return the child value stored under name in a table node, or 0

    Let keys be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with table_node, 48
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with table_node, 40

    If keys is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If children is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc size from List with keys
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let key be proc get_at from List with keys, index
        Let matches be proc string_equals with key, name

        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return proc get_at from List with children, index
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Adding a (key, value) pair to a table appends to the two parallel lists in
lockstep so index i always pairs keys[i] with children[i] -- the invariant the
translator depends on.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read keys/children lists; append the (already heap-owned) key to keys and the
value node to children.
@End Implementation

Process called "table_add_child" takes table_node as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Append a key/value pair to a table node's parallel lists

    Let keys be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with table_node, 48
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with table_node, 40

    proc append from List with keys, key
    proc append from List with children, value

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A single bare-key segment that names a sub-table is resolved get-or-create:
if a child table already exists under it, reuse it (so [a] then [a.b] merge);
otherwise create a fresh TOML_TABLE, attach it, and return it. An owned copy
of the segment name is taken because the lexeme buffer it came from is
transient.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Look up name in table_node. If found and it is a TOML_TABLE, return it. If
found but not a table, that is a redefinition conflict reported by the caller
via 0. If absent, allocate an owned copy of name, create a TOML_TABLE, attach
under the copied key, and return the new table.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_or_create_subtable" takes parser as Integer, table_node as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get-or-create a child TOML_TABLE under name; 0 on conflict/OOM

    Let existing be proc table_find_child with table_node, name

    If existing is not equal to 0:
        Let existing_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with existing, 0

        If existing_type is equal to TOML_TABLE:
            Return existing
        End If

        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Key redefined as a table"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Copy the segment name (lexeme buffer is transient)
    Let name_len be proc string_length from StringCore with name
    Let name_copy be proc allocate from Layout with name_len plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with name_copy, name, name_len
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with name_copy, name_len, 0

    Let subtable be proc create_table_node with TOML_TABLE

    If subtable is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc table_add_child with table_node, name_copy, subtable

    Return subtable
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Key Parsing (bare and quoted, dotted)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A single key segment is either a bare identifier or a quoted string (basic or
literal); both arrive from the lexer as TOKEN_IDENTIFIER and TOKEN_STRING
respectively with the resolved bytes in the lexeme slot. Returning an owned
copy keeps the key alive past the transient token.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the current token type. For TOKEN_IDENTIFIER or TOKEN_STRING, copy the
lexeme into an owned NUL-terminated buffer, advance, and return it. Any other
token sets "Expected key" and returns 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_key_segment" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse one key segment (bare or quoted), returning an owned copy

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    Let is_ident be 0
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
        Set is_ident to 1
    End If
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Set is_ident to 1
    End If

    If is_ident is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected key"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let key_copy be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with key_copy, lexeme, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with key_copy, lexeme_length, 0

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return key_copy
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Value Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
TOML values are first-token-dispatchable: scalars have unique TOKEN_* tags, '['
opens an array, '{' opens an inline table; one switch handles every form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspect the current token type. Map TOKEN_STRING/INTEGER/FLOAT/BOOLEAN/DATETIME
to the corresponding parse_* helper; TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET -> parse_array;
TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE -> parse_inline_table. Unknown tags record "Expected value"
and return 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_value" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse TOML value (string, number, boolean, array, inline table)

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_string with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_INTEGER from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_integer with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_FLOAT from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_float with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_BOOLEAN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_boolean with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_DATETIME from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_datetime with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_array with parser
    End If

    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_inline_table with parser
    End If

    proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected value"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
String parsing has already happened in the lexer (escapes resolved, quotes
stripped); the parser only needs to capture the resolved lexeme into the node,
defending against the lexer's buffer being reused by copying.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the token's lexeme pointer, length, and source position. Allocate a fresh
length+1 byte buffer, copy the lexeme bytes, null-terminate. Build a
TOML_STRING node, attach the copy at offset 8, store line/column. Advance.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_string" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse TOML string

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let node be proc create_toml_node with TOML_STRING

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_copy be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with value_copy, lexeme, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value_copy, lexeme_length, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value_copy
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, column

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
TOML supports decimal, hex (0x), octal (0o), binary (0b), and underscored
numeric literals; running parse_integer_value once at parse time avoids
re-parsing the lexeme each time the integer is read.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Build a TOML_INTEGER node. Call parse_integer_value on the lexeme to convert to
a 64-bit int. Store the integer at offset 16, set is_integer=1, store
line/column, advance.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_integer" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse TOML integer

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let node be proc create_toml_node with TOML_INTEGER

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value be proc parse_integer_value with lexeme

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 1  Note: is_integer = true
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, column

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
TOML floats may include special values (inf, nan, -inf), exponents, and
underscores; preserving the source string and deferring conversion to the HIR
float-literal constructor keeps every format intact without re-parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Build a TOML_FLOAT node. Allocate length+1 bytes, copy the lexeme,
null-terminate. Store the copy at offset 8, set is_float=1 at offset 32, store
line/column, advance.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_float" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse TOML float

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let node be proc create_toml_node with TOML_FLOAT

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_copy be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with value_copy, lexeme, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value_copy, lexeme_length, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value_copy
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 1  Note: is_float = true
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, column

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
TOML booleans are spelt only "true" or "false" (case-sensitive); a single
string-equality check against "true" plus default-to-0 covers both cases.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Build a TOML_BOOLEAN node. Compare the lexeme to "true" via string_equals;
store 1 at offset 16 on match, 0 otherwise. Store line/column, advance.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_boolean" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse TOML boolean

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let node be proc create_toml_node with TOML_BOOLEAN

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_true be proc string_equals with lexeme, "true"

    If is_true is equal to 1:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 1
    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, column

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
TOML's four datetime sub-forms (offset datetime, local datetime, local date,
local time) carry timezone and precision distinctions that survive only in the
raw RFC 3339 string; copying the lexeme preserves the exact source
representation for downstream conversion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Build a TOML_DATETIME node. Allocate length+1 bytes, copy the datetime lexeme,
null-terminate, attach at offset 8, store line/column, advance.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_datetime" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse TOML datetime (RFC 3339)

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let node be proc create_toml_node with TOML_DATETIME

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_copy be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with value_copy, lexeme, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with value_copy, lexeme_length, 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value_copy
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, column

    proc advance_token with parser

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
TOML arrays "[v1, v2, ...]" allow newlines between elements but require a comma
between elements (a trailing comma is permitted before the closing bracket); a
per-element loop with explicit newline-skip handles all of these.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Expect '['. Allocate a TOML_ARRAY node and an empty children list. Skip
newlines. Loop: if current is ']' break; recursively parse_value as element,
append to children, skip newlines; if next token is comma advance and skip
newlines, otherwise break. Expect ']'.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in array length; one node allocation per element plus the array node.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_array" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse TOML array: [value1, value2, ...]

    Let ok_open be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer, "Expected '['"

    If ok_open is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node be proc create_toml_node with TOML_ARRAY

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, children

    proc skip_newlines with parser

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_close be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer

        If is_close is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Let element be proc parse_value with parser

        If element is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc append from List with children, element

        proc skip_newlines with parser

        Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
            proc skip_newlines with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let ok_close be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer, "Expected ']'"

    If ok_close is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Inline tables "{ k1 = v1, k2 = v2 }" must be parsed on a single line per TOML
1.0; the parallel keys and children lists let downstream consumers read entries
with one index without dictionary overhead.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Expect '{'. Allocate a TOML_INLINE_TABLE node with parallel keys and children
lists. Loop: if current is '}' break; parse one (possibly quoted) key segment,
expect TOKEN_EQUAL, recursively parse_value, append key and value to their
respective lists; if next is comma advance and continue, otherwise break.
Expect '}'.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_inline_table" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse TOML inline table: {key = value, key2 = value2}

    Let ok_open be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE from Lexer, "Expected '{'"

    If ok_open is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node be proc create_table_node with TOML_INLINE_TABLE

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_close be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer

        If is_close is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Let key_copy be proc parse_key_segment with parser

        If key_copy is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let ok_eq be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer, "Expected '='"

        If ok_eq is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let value_node be proc parse_value with parser

        If value_node is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc table_add_child with node, key_copy, value_node

        Let is_comma be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_COMMA from Lexer

        If is_comma is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let ok_close be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE from Lexer, "Expected '}'"

    If ok_close is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Table Header Navigation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A "[a.b.c]" header navigates from the document root, creating intermediate
tables, and returns the leaf table that subsequent key/value pairs attach to.
Resolving the path through get_or_create_subtable means a later "[a.b]" header
re-finds the same intermediate tables created by "[a.b.c]" (and vice versa),
which is the merging behaviour TOML requires.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Expect '['. Starting from root, loop reading key segments separated by '.':
for each segment, descend via get_or_create_subtable; if a '.' follows, consume
it and continue, otherwise the segment is the leaf. Expect ']'. Return the leaf
table node (0 on conflict/syntax error).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Each segment name is heap-copied with an exact length, so adversarial dotted
paths only consume bounded memory per segment.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_table_header" takes parser as Integer, root as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse [a.b.c] header, return the leaf table node

    Let ok_open be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer, "Expected '['"

    If ok_open is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current be root

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let segment be proc parse_key_segment with parser

        If segment is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let next_table be proc get_or_create_subtable with parser, current, segment

        Note: get_or_create_subtable copied the name; free our segment copy
        proc deallocate from Layout with segment

        If next_table is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set current to next_table

        Let is_dot be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DOT from Lexer

        If is_dot is equal to 1:
            proc advance_token with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let ok_close be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer, "Expected ']'"

    If ok_close is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return current
End Process

@Reasoning:
A "[[a.b.c]]" header navigates to the parent table "a.b", then treats "c" as an
array-of-tables: get-or-create a TOML_ARRAY at that slot, append a fresh
TOML_TABLE element, and make that element the active table. Repeated
"[[a.b.c]]" headers append additional table elements to the same array.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Expect TOKEN_ARRAY_TABLE_HEADER (consumes "[["). Read the first segment;
loop: peek for a following '.'. While a dot follows, descend into the segment
as an intermediate table and read the next segment. The final segment names
the array-of-tables: look it up; if absent create a TOML_ARRAY and attach it;
if present require it to be a TOML_ARRAY. Append a fresh TOML_TABLE element to
the array. Expect ']' ']'. Return the new table element.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Shares the per-segment exact-length heap copy with parse_table_header.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_array_table_header" takes parser as Integer, root as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse [[a.b.c]] header, append a table element, return it

    Let ok_open be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_ARRAY_TABLE_HEADER from Lexer, "Expected '[['"

    If ok_open is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current be root
    Let segment be proc parse_key_segment with parser

    If segment is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Descend through all intermediate segments (those followed by '.')
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_dot be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DOT from Lexer

        If is_dot is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser

        Let next_table be proc get_or_create_subtable with parser, current, segment
        proc deallocate from Layout with segment

        If next_table is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set current to next_table
        Set segment to proc parse_key_segment with parser

        If segment is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End While

    Note: segment now names the array-of-tables in table `current`
    Let array_node be proc table_find_child with current, segment

    If array_node is equal to 0:
        Note: Create the array-of-tables slot
        Let seg_len be proc string_length from StringCore with segment
        Let seg_copy be proc allocate from Layout with seg_len plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with seg_copy, segment, seg_len
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with seg_copy, seg_len, 0

        Set array_node to proc create_toml_node with TOML_ARRAY

        If array_node is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
            Return 0
        End If

        Let arr_children be proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with array_node, 40, arr_children

        proc table_add_child with current, seg_copy, array_node
    Otherwise:
        Let array_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with array_node, 0

        If array_type is not equal to TOML_ARRAY:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Key redefined as array of tables"
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with segment

    Note: Append a fresh table element to the array
    Let element_table be proc create_table_node with TOML_TABLE

    If element_table is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let arr_list be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with array_node, 40
    proc append from List with arr_list, element_table

    Let ok_c1 be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer, "Expected ']'"

    If ok_c1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ok_c2 be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET from Lexer, "Expected ']'"

    If ok_c2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return element_table
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Key-Value Pair Parsing (with dotted keys)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A "key = value" statement may use a dotted key (a.b.c = value), which creates
the same nesting as "[a.b]" then "c = value" but scoped under the active table.
Resolving the dotted prefix through get_or_create_subtable on the active table
keeps dotted keys and table headers consistent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parse the first key segment. While a '.' follows, descend into the segment as a
subtable of the active table and read the next segment. The final segment is
the value key: parse '=' then the value, and attach (final_key, value) to the
table reached by the descent (the active table if there was no dot). Detect a
duplicate final key as a redefinition error.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_key_value_into" takes parser as Integer, table_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse key[.key]* = value and attach into table_node; returns 1/0

    Let current be table_node
    Let segment be proc parse_key_segment with parser

    If segment is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_dot be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_DOT from Lexer

        If is_dot is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser

        Let next_table be proc get_or_create_subtable with parser, current, segment
        proc deallocate from Layout with segment

        If next_table is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set current to next_table
        Set segment to proc parse_key_segment with parser

        If segment is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End While

    Let ok_eq be proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUAL from Lexer, "Expected '='"

    If ok_eq is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with segment
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_node be proc parse_value with parser

    If value_node is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with segment
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Reject duplicate key in this table (redefinition)
    Let existing be proc table_find_child with current, segment

    If existing is not equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Duplicate key"
        proc deallocate from Layout with segment
        Return 0
    End If

    proc table_add_child with current, segment, value_node

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Document Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A TOML file is a sequence of statements distinguished by their leading token:
'[' opens a [table] header, '[[' opens an [[array-of-tables]] header, and an
identifier or quoted string opens a key/value pair. The parser tracks the
active table so subsequent key/value pairs attach under the right node, and
builds a genuinely nested tree the translator can lower to nested HIR
dictionaries and arrays.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Build a root TOML_DOCUMENT node with parallel keys/children lists. Set the
active table to the root. Loop: skip newlines; on EOF break; on '[' parse a
table header (rebinding the active table to the returned leaf); on '[[' parse
an array-table header (rebinding to the appended element); on identifier/string
parse a key/value pair into the active table. Unknown tokens record "Unexpected
token" and abort.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in source token count; allocations are bounded by the document structure.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Consumes untrusted TOML source. Unknown tokens halt the parse cleanly via
set_parse_error; every key/table name is heap-copied with an exact length.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_document" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse TOML document into a nested table tree

    Let document be proc create_table_node with TOML_DOCUMENT

    If document is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Active table starts at the document root
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, document

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_newlines with parser

        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type with parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Table header [a.b.c]
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET from Lexer:
            Let leaf be proc parse_table_header with parser, document

            If leaf is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, leaf
            proc skip_newlines with parser
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Array of tables header [[a.b.c]]
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_ARRAY_TABLE_HEADER from Lexer:
            Let element be proc parse_array_table_header with parser, document

            If element is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 32, element
            proc skip_newlines with parser
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Key-value pair (bare or quoted key)
        Let is_kv be 0
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER from Lexer:
            Set is_kv to 1
        End If
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_STRING from Lexer:
            Set is_kv to 1
        End If

        If is_kv is equal to 1:
            Let active be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 32
            Let ok_kv be proc parse_key_value_into with parser, active

            If ok_kv is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            proc skip_newlines with parser
            Continue
        End If

        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Unexpected token"
        Return 0
    End While

    Return document
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Utility Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
TOML integers support four bases (decimal, 0x hex, 0o octal, 0b binary) plus an
optional leading sign and underscore-separators; doing the conversion once at
parse time lets parse_integer cache the integer in the node and skip per-read
re-parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skip optional leading '+' or '-' (record sign). If the next char is '0'
followed by 'x' / 'o' / 'b', enter the appropriate base loop: accumulate
digit*base+digit for each digit char, skip underscores. Otherwise treat the
rest as decimal digits. Apply the sign and return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in digit count; no allocation, all work in 64-bit accumulators.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_integer_value" takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse integer from string (handles decimal, hex, octal, binary)

    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with str

    If length is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let index be 0
    Let is_negative be 0
    Let value be 0

    Let first_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str, 0

    If first_char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Set is_negative to 1
        Set index to 1
    Otherwise If first_char is equal to 43:  Note: +
        Set index to 1
    End If

    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str, index

    If char is equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        If index plus 1 is less than length:
            Let prefix be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str, index plus 1

            If prefix is equal to 120:  Note: 'x' hexadecimal
                Set index to index plus 2
                While index is less than length:
                    Set char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str, index
                    Let digit be 0

                    If char is greater than or equal to 48 and char is less than or equal to 57:
                        Set digit to char minus 48
                    Otherwise If char is greater than or equal to 65 and char is less than or equal to 70:
                        Set digit to char minus 65 plus 10
                    Otherwise If char is greater than or equal to 97 and char is less than or equal to 102:
                        Set digit to char minus 97 plus 10
                    Otherwise If char is equal to 95:  Note: '_'
                        Set index to index plus 1
                        Continue
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If

                    Set value to value multiplied by 16 plus digit
                    Set index to index plus 1
                End While

                If is_negative is equal to 1:
                    Set value to -value
                End If
                Return value

            Otherwise If prefix is equal to 111:  Note: 'o' octal
                Set index to index plus 2
                While index is less than length:
                    Set char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str, index

                    If char is greater than or equal to 48 and char is less than or equal to 55:
                        Set digit to char minus 48
                        Set value to value multiplied by 8 plus digit
                        Set index to index plus 1
                    Otherwise If char is equal to 95:
                        Set index to index plus 1
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End While

                If is_negative is equal to 1:
                    Set value to -value
                End If
                Return value

            Otherwise If prefix is equal to 98:  Note: 'b' binary
                Set index to index plus 2
                While index is less than length:
                    Set char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str, index

                    If char is equal to 48:  Note: '0'
                        Set value to value multiplied by 2
                        Set index to index plus 1
                    Otherwise If char is equal to 49:  Note: '1'
                        Set value to value multiplied by 2 plus 1
                        Set index to index plus 1
                    Otherwise If char is equal to 95:
                        Set index to index plus 1
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End While

                If is_negative is equal to 1:
                    Set value to -value
                End If
                Return value
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse decimal
    While index is less than length:
        Set char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str, index

        If char is greater than or equal to 48:
            If char is less than or equal to 57:
                Set digit to char minus 48
                Set value to value multiplied by 10
                Set value to value plus digit
                Set index to index plus 1
            Otherwise If char is equal to 95:
                Set index to index plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    If is_negative is equal to 1:
        Set value to -value
    End If

    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning:
parse_boolean and the table navigation helpers need byte-for-byte content
equality between two NUL-terminated strings; an inline loop avoids depending on
StringCore's comparison primitives in these hot paths.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Measure both strings; on length mismatch return 0. Otherwise compare byte by
byte; return 0 on the first mismatch, 1 if all bytes match.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_equals" takes str1 as Integer, str2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if two strings are equal

    Let len1 be proc string_length from StringCore with str1
    Let len2 be proc string_length from StringCore with str2

    If len1 is not equal to len2:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let index be 0

    While index is less than len1:
        Let char1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str1, index
        Let char2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str2, index

        If char1 is not equal to char2:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Parsing Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point that hides the lex+parse orchestration and the lexer/parser
cleanup obligations; callers receive either the document node on success or 0
on failure. The 0-return contract is how failure is surfaced to the
import-cycle-free backends and the dispatcher.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-check source. Create a TOML lexer; on failure return 0. Create a parser;
on failure destroy the lexer and return 0. Run parse_document. If has_error is
set, destroy both and return 0. Otherwise destroy both and return the document.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Consumes untrusted TOML source. The cleanup path runs on every failure exit to
prevent leaks.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_toml" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse TOML source code to AST

    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let lexer be proc create_toml_lexer from Lexer with source

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser be proc create_toml_parser with lexer

    If parser is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_toml_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        Return 0
    End If

    Let document be proc parse_document with parser

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24

    If has_error is equal to 1:
        proc destroy_toml_parser with parser
        proc destroy_toml_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        Return 0
    End If

    proc destroy_toml_parser with parser
    proc destroy_toml_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    Return document
End Process

Note: End of TOML Parser
